    <note>Zhang(2) Liang [7159] Under Cai Jing [1649], his brother, Yan [3190], was accused of conspiracy to counterfeit coins with a prefectural neighbor Yu(11) Bao [4130] and branded on the face and sent to Shamen prison island. Liang and his brothers were all dismissed from the civil service and exiled to various places. When Zhang(1) Shangying [272] became chief councillor, the case was reviewed by an investigating censor, Xiao(1) Dingji's [723] grandson Fu [3364], and the decision reversed. Liang was Jie(3)'s [345] son, Wang(2) Shu(1)'s [1877] great grandson-in-law (twice: sororate ?) and Sun(1) Di's [7343] father-in-law. His brother Zai's [3189] father-in-law was He Bifei [7235]. Liang's grandson, Tan [3188], was Guangdong tiju in 1170 and rose to Guangxi yunpan in 1172. Guangdong TZ, 15.20a; Shengzheng, 52.7a; SS, 328.31a-31b; Sun Di, Daquanji, 56.13a; Sun Di, WJ, 33.3b, 6a ff; Suzhou FZ, 77.18b. CBD, 3, 2082.</note>
